## State Management Architecture

### 1. Global State (@preact/signals)

**Purpose:** Manage UI state that needs to be accessed across the entire application.

**Location:** `src/shared/store/globalStore.ts`

**Implementation:**
```typescript
import { signal } from '@preact/signals-core';

export const globalStore = {
  [GlobalStoreFieldE.AUTH_TOKEN]: signal<string | null>(null),
  [GlobalStoreFieldE.NOTIFICATIONS]: signal<NotificationT[]>([]),
  [GlobalStoreFieldE.MODALS]: signal<ModalT[]>([]),
  [GlobalStoreFieldE.IDS_LIST]: signal<SaveRemovalT>({}),
  [GlobalStoreFieldE.SIDEBAR]: signal<SidebarT[]>([]),
};
```

**Key Features:**
- **Reactive:** Components re-render automatically when signal changes
- **Type-Safe:** Each field has a defined type
- **Fast:** Minimal re-renders, only subscribed components update
- **Dev Tools:** Store exposed to `window.globalStore` in development

**Access Pattern:**
```typescript
// Read state in component
const token = useGlobalValue(GlobalStoreFieldE.AUTH_TOKEN);

// Update state in service
const updateToken = createGlobalValueSetter(GlobalStoreFieldE.AUTH_TOKEN);
updateToken('new-token-value');
```

**Why @preact/signals:**
- Lightweight (~1KB)
- Framework-agnostic core
- No Context providers needed
- Fine-grained reactivity
- Better performance than Context API

